# Engineering Instructions

## Non-negotiables
- Production-grade only. No tutorial/demo implementations.
- Analyze repo structure and follow existing conventions before writing any code.
- Reuse project abstractions; never introduce inconsistent patterns.

## Architecture
- Thin controllers → business logic in services → data access in repositories
- Validators/schemas are separate; utilities are generic and reusable
- SOLID principles, composition over inheritance, small focused functions

## Code quality
- Meaningful names, self-documenting code, no duplicated logic
- Dependency injection for testability; deterministic, isolated business logic

## Performance & memory
- Stream / chunk / paginate large data — never load full datasets into memory
- No unbounded caches, unnecessary object creation, or blocking operations
- Prefer lazy loading, cursors, iterators, backpressure-aware processing

## Resilience
- Defensive error handling on all critical paths — never swallow errors silently
- Timeout + retry handling; idempotent, retry-safe, duplicate-safe operations
- Graceful degradation and circuit-breaker-friendly patterns

## Security
- Validate and sanitize all external input; never trust client data
- No hardcoded secrets — use env vars / secret managers
- Never log sensitive data or expose stack traces to clients
- Auth + authorization + ownership checks before any sensitive operation

## Database
- No N+1 queries; indexed access; fetch only required fields
- Paginate large reads; no unbounded table scans; transactions used carefully
- Prefer bulk operations; handle concurrency safely

## Async / queues / workers
- Idempotent message handling with dead-letter and partial failure recovery
- Correlation IDs on all async flows; safe acknowledgements; graceful shutdown
- Workers must recover cleanly after crash or restart

## Observability
- Structured logging with requestId, correlationId, traceId where relevant
- Log failures, retries, and key state transitions — not noise, not sensitive data

## API design
- Correct HTTP status codes; consistent response structure; meaningful errors
- Validate all requests; never leak internal details; preserve existing contracts

## Configuration
- No hardcoded environments; validate critical config at startup; fail fast

## Dependencies
- Stable, maintained, battle-tested libraries only
- No unnecessary or deprecated packages
